      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>Henry Martin Formhals (1908-1981) was an American cartoonist. Beginning in 1935, he served as assistant on Merrill  Blosser's newspaper comic strip <emph render="italic">Freckles and His Friends</emph>. Formhals' name officially appeared on the strip in the mid 1960s (March 21, 1966), and he continued to work on it until the end of its run in 1971.     Over the course of his career, Formhals also worked on the <emph render="italic">Joe Jinks</emph> strip (1946-1953) and assisted on Charlie Plumb's <emph render="italic">Ella Cinders</emph>.</p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Henry Formhals Cartoons</emph> collection contains original daily (1966-1967) and Sunday (1967-1968) cartoons from the newspaper comic strip <emph render="italic">Freckles and His Friends</emph>. Sunday versions of the strip include the companion title <emph render="italic">Hector</emph>. Daily cartoon: blue pencil, traces of graphite, brush, pen and ink on illustration board, approx. 6 x 17 Â¼ in. Sunday cartoon: blue pencil, traces of graphite, brush, pen and ink on illustration board, approx. 19 x 26 in.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      
      <arrangement encodinganalog="351$a">
         <head>Arrangement of the Collection</head>
         <p>Daily and Sunday strips are housed separately in chronological order.</p>
      </arrangement>
      
      <relatedmaterial encodinganalog="544 1">
         <head>Related Material</head>
